No one who I have ever spoken with at McKesson gives me the impression that there is any accountability for the quality of their work or performance with respect to serving customers. But I don't believe the fault lies with these individuals. This is a direct result of management creating a culture that aims to reduce problems by instructing staff to do a minimum amount of work that makes problems 'go away', without actually addressing the root issues that create the problems. Ultimately as with most enterprises like this, it comes down to a willingness from the top to hire enough staff, pay them a decent wage, and train them that customer service is the priority. As someone who provides customer service every day, being enabled by management to put customers first is a wonderful feeling. You simply have to invest in your staff properly, which requires spending more money. With the levels of revenue and profit that McKesson generates, this goal is easily attainable. It simply requires a willingness from the top to achieve that goal.
